ture) in conversation with relocation debates in other places such Quebec and Northern Canada, Greenland, and Ireland. Contributors consider common themes of contemporary resettlement programs including resistance, collective-decision-making, power, place, and identity. Newfoundland Studies scholars have underscored the significance of Smallwood-era resettlement programs (1954–1977), but have not yet adequately addressed the second, ongoing phase of resettlement (1977–present), carried out at the request of communities and implemented to mitigate the fiscal mismatch between shrinking populations and infrastructure costs. In these pages, scholars examine a process that begins before and continues long after communities or individuals move, and places the Newfoundland and Labrador experience in conversation with other global contemporary resettlement projects.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMigration, InternalzNewfoundland and Labrador. 0aMigration, Internal. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Rural.2bisacsh1 aArnfjord, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarry, Hannah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristensen, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCôté, Isabelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCôté, Isabelle, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLeDrew, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoo, Tina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarshall, Nicole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPottie-Sherman, Yolande, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPottie-Sherman, Yolande, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/v